  "prompt": "What is the electric potential at the centre of sphere?",
  "response": "The electric potential at the center of a sphere depends on the charge distribution of the sphere:\n\n1. **Solid Conducting Sphere**: If the sphere is a solid conductor with a total charge \\( Q \\), the electric potential \\( V \\) at the center, or anywhere inside the sphere, is constant and equal to the potential on the surface of the sphere. This is because the charge resides only on the surface and the electric field inside a conductor in electrostatic equilibrium is zero. The potential at the center is given by:\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R}\n   \\]\n   where \\( R \\) is the radius of the sphere and \\( \\varepsilon_0 \\) is the permittivity of free space.\n\n2. **Solid Non-Conducting (Dielectric) Sphere**: If the sphere is a non-conducting solid with a uniform volume charge density \\( \\rho \\), the potential at the center is different. You need to integrate the contributions to the potential from each infinitesimally small charge element in the volume of the sphere.\n\n   If you complete this integration from the center of the sphere out to a radius \\( R \\), you find:\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{2R}\n   \\]\n   where \\( Q \\) is the total charge of the sphere.\n\n3. **Hollow Conducting Sphere**: If the sphere is a hollow conductor, the potential inside (including at the center) is again the same as at the surface:\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R}\n   \\]\n\nIn all cases, the reference point (where the potential is zero) is typically considered to be at infinity. The precise formula depends on the nature of the sphere and the charge distribution.",
